We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. Direct the Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Property Division/Unit and Municipal Accounting Office, to prepare a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) containing, at the least, the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, the cut-off date and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory;
b. Require the submission of the PIP duly approved by the Local Chief Executive to the Audit Team at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;
c. Cause the immediate and timely conduct of the physical count of all PPEs in accordance with the approved PIP to determine their existence and condition;
d. Ensure that property records are updated based on the results of the physical inventory per RPCPPE and reconciled with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts;
e. Require the OIC- Municipal Accountant to ensure that all PPEs subject for depreciation are provided with depreciation expense; and
f. Oblige the Inventory Committee to submit to the Audit Team the RPCPPE duly reconciled with the accounting and property records, not later than the 10th day of January of the following year.

