We recommend that management:

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer and reconcile records of prior years’ completed projects which are still included in the CIP; 

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to secure from the Municipal Engineer Certificate of Completion and Certificate of Turnover and Acceptance on the validated completed projects to be used as basis in the reclassification of the CIP accounts to the proper PPE account;

Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to take up the corresponding depreciation expenses based on updated completed projects from the date of completion until December 31, 2022, and prepare adjusting entry as necessary;

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to effect the following adjusting entry to close the completed Public Infrastructures to the Government Equity and transfer the same to the Registry of Public Infrastructures; and

Observe and follow strictly the prescribed accounting entries provided under the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volumes I and III in transferring the completed Public Infrastructure to the Registry of Infrastructures at the end of the year to reflect the correct account balances in the year-end financial statements.

We recommended and the management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Health Officer and/or concerned RHU personnel to furnished the Municpal OIC-Accountant, the documents necessary to record the receipt and distribution of vaccines, ancillaries and supplies Inventory Report  or its equivalent in relation to the vaccination program;
Direct the Municipal OIC-Accountant to record using the perpetual inventory system, the vaccines received and its distribution as reported by the LGU       to DOH-CHD; and draw journal entry voucher for the applicable inventory accounts to record the remaining supplies of vaccines in stock at       December 31, 2021.

Exert effort in the processing of Certificate of Title of the untitled lots in order to establish absolute ownership and protect the legal interest of the LGU   pursuant to Section 148 of COA Circular 92-386;

Set aside fund for the titling of these lots and direct the Municipal Treasurer to facilitate and supervise the proper payments of expenses for the land titling and to update and reconcile the inventory of property assets with the updated records of the OIC-Municipal Accountant.

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to record the subject lots based on fair market value of the land.

Initiate the payment of employees’ salaries, allowances, fringe benefits and other    emoluments through bank;

Make a representation with any government bank for an opening of individual ATM savings accounts by employees through a Memorandum of Agreement; and

Adopt the payroll-thru-bank scheme upon approval of the Memorandum of Agreement.

Cause the monitoring of GAD activities and constant reconciliation with accounting records to come up with a reliable GAD report;

Submit a copy of the corresponding annual GAD accomplishment report to the  Audit Team within five (5) working days from the end of January of the preceding year; and

Henceforth, comply strictly with Sections 4.8 and 5.2 of Joint Circular No. 2004-1 dated April 5, 2004 of DBM, NEDA, and NCRFW.

Require the Inventory Committee to submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team; 

Cause the reconciliation of the property records with the accounting records and effect necessary adjustments, if any;

Require the OIC Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to immediately maintain PPELC and PC, respectively, per category of property, plant and equipment, pursuant to Sections 119 and 120 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume I;

Cause the immediate submission of the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property and the Request for Relief from Accountability for loss of property, damaged during Typhoon Yolanda; and 

Conduct inventory of the totally damaged property and submit the report to the disposal committee of the Municipal Government of Ivisan as contemplated under Section 79 of P.D. 1445, for appropriate action.

